==English==
===Adjective===
'''non-U'''
#(''mostly British'') not [[U]]; not characteristic of the [[upper class]]es, particularly regarding [[language]].

===Quotations===
* '''1992,''' John Algeo, “Sociolinguistic Attitudes and Issues in Contemporary Britain,” in ''English in Its Social Contexts,'' Tim W Machan and Charles T Scott edd. [http://books.google.com/books?ie=UTF-8&hl=en&id=Bhv3PPQlOa0C&pg=PA165&lpg=PA165&sig=8bMmsYZwRxMWPZuDZZu4lVBROUg]
*: The concept of U (for upper-class British usage, as opposed to '''non-U''', or everything else) was introduced by Alan S. C. Ross (1954) and was taken up by Nancy Mitford (1956), becoming for a time something of a parlor game in which the participants tested themselves and everyone else for signs of U and '''non-U''' status.
* '''2001,''' Stephan Gramley, ''The Vocabulary of World English'' [http://books.google.com/books?ie=UTF-8&hl=en&id=AjiEXHA-eXoC&pg=PA205&lpg=PA205&sig=X15vqYokVJjL0w1D2b7nfZc-kt8]
*: For this we must turn to speculations such as those offered in connection with U and '''non-U''' English.
* '''2003,''' Philip Pettit, ''Rules, Reasons, and Norms'' [http://books.google.com/books?ie=UTF-8&hl=en&id=Mq7K1hiB3WIC&pg=RA1-PA78&lpg=RA1-PA78&sig=adF93764CE75acmwxVYM21a0ZWQ]
*: To speak of lavatories is U, of bathrooms '''non-U'''; to lay cloth napkins at table is U, to lay paper napkins '''non-U'''; and so on through a myriad of equally trivial examples.

